    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc" resp="#JP">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><orig>ΩΝ</orig>
                    <lb n="2"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><orig><unclear>Π</unclear>ΑΤΡ</orig>
                    <lb n="3"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><supplied reason="lost">ἐ</supplied>κκ τῶν
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app><note>Text after ISegesta G25</note></app>
                    <app loc="2"><note>Nenci: [---]ἰατρῶν; SEG after Nenci: [---]ἰατρ[ῶν]; Ampolo and Erdas note only a vertical stroke is visible at the start, but that more likely is e.g. [--Σώ]πατρ- vel sim.</note></app>
                 </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p><!--translation(s) - add @xml:lang for 'en' or 'it' to div--></p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Nenci suggested emending κκ in line 3 to ἐκ but Ampolo and Erdas note that gemination of the κ is well attested. Ampolo and Erdas suggest that the word ἰδίων may have stood in the first part of the line (4) below line 3, which is empty on the stone; but if the text extended onto a second stone, as is implied by line 2, then it could equally have followed on line 3. The proposed early imperial date is based solely on letter forms.</p>
            </div>
